urls.description: Data Analysis Using Regression and Multilevel/Hierarchical Models is a comprehensive manual for the applied researcher who wants to perform data analysis using linear and nonlinear regression and multilevel models. The book introduces a wide variety of models, whilst at the same time instructing the reader in how to fit these models using available software packages. The book illustrates the concepts by working through scores of real data examples that have arisen from the authors' own applied research, with programming codes provided for each one. urls.description: Extremely efficient procedures for fitting the entire lasso or elastic-net regularization path for linear regression, logistic and multinomial regression models, Poisson regression, Cox model, multiple-response Gaussian, and the grouped multinomial regression; see <doi:10.18637/jss.v033.i01> and <doi:10.18637/jss.v039.i05>. There are two new and important additions. The family argument can be a GLM family object, which opens the door to any programmed family (<doi:10.18637/jss.v106.i01>). This comes with a modest computational cost, so when the built-in families suffice, they should be used instead. The other novelty is the relax option, which refits each of the active sets in the path unpenalized. The algorithm uses cyclical coordinate descent in a path-wise fashion, as described in the papers cited.

urls.description: Summarizes key information about statistical objects in tidy tibbles. This makes it easy to report results, create plots and consistently work with large numbers of models at once. Broom provides three verbs that each provide different types of information about a model. tidy() summarizes information about model components such as coefficients of a regression. glance() reports information about an entire model, such as goodness of fit measures like AIC and BIC. augment() adds information about individual observations to a dataset, such as fitted values or influence measures.

text: 9/ Regularization methods are essential tools for machine learning practitioners, and R provides a user-friendly environment for implementing these methods. Using these methods can help to improve model accuracy and interpretability, leading to better decision-making. #rstats

8/ Regularization methods are especially useful when dealing with high-dimensional data, where the number of features is much larger than the number of observations. They help to improve model performance and reduce the risk of overfitting. #rstats

7/ Here, we first create the model matrix x and the response vector y. We then use the glmnet function with alpha = 1 to fit a Lasso regression model. Similarly, we can fit a Ridge or Elastic Net model by setting alpha to 0 or a value between 0 and 1, respectively.
#rstats

6/ For example, to fit a Lasso regression model in R, we can use the following code:
>library(glmnet) x <- >model.matrix(Sepal.Width ~ ., data = iris)
>y <- iris$Sepal.Width 
>lasso_model <- glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1)
> plot(lasso_model)
#rstats https://t.co/sPQWsBRwfb

5/ These regularization methods can be easily implemented in R using the glmnet package. The glmnet function allows for fitting generalized linear models with Lasso, Ridge, and Elastic Net regularization. #rstats

4/ Elastic Net is a combination of Lasso and Ridge. It uses a combination of L1 and L2 regularization to create a balance between sparse models and models that retain all features. It is useful when there are many features, and some of them are highly correlated. #rstats

3/ Ridge regression, on the other hand, uses L2 regularization to add a penalty term to the loss function that shrinks the coefficients of less important features towards zero without setting them to zero. It is useful when all features are potentially relevant. #rstats

2/ Lasso (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator) is a method that uses L1 regularization to shrink the coefficients of less important features to zero, resulting in a sparse model. It is useful when there are many features with only a few of them being relevant. #rstats
